        "text": "The 1932–3 ‘Miracle of Wörgl’ – named after the Austrian town in which it occurred – is one of the best-known examples of a community currency stimulating the local economy. In the midst of the Great Depression’s monetary contraction, the town’s new mayor, Michael Unterguggenberger, issued a town currency incorporating [[demurrage]]."
      },
